# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fish-stocks
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] Acoustic tags transmit a signal made up of acoustic pulses or "pings" that send positional information of the tagged organism to a hydrophone receiver.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] By tying the received acoustic frequency to a predetermined and unique signal code, tagged animals can be identified at an individual level.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] Transmitted signals may propagate up to 1 km (in freshwater) depending on tag model and environmental conditions.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] Receivers can be actively held by a researcher ("Active Tracking") or affixed to specific locations ("Passive Tracking").
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] Arrays of receivers can allow the triangulation of tagged individuals over many kilometers.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] Acoustic tags are produced in many different shapes and sizes depending on the study organism or study environment.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] The battery life of acoustic tags varies by size, with some larger tags lasting over four years.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] Sound parameters such as frequency and modulation method are chosen for optimal detectability and signal level.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] For oceanic environments, frequencies less than 100 kHz range are often used, while frequencies of several hundreds of kilohertz are more common in for studies in rivers and lakes.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] A typical acoustic tag consists of a piezoceramic transducer, drive/timing electronics, and a battery power source.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] Cylindrical or “tube” transducers are often used, which have metalization on the inner and outer walls of the structure.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] In normal operation, an alternating current (AC) electrical signal generated by the drive/timing electronics is impressed across the two metalization layers.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] This voltage creates stress in the material, which in turn cause the transducer to emit an acoustic signal or “ping”, which emanates outward from the surface of the tube.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] An acoustic “ping” can be detected by specialized receivers, and processed using advanced signal processing techniques to determine if a fish swimming into the reception area carries a specific acoustic tag.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] Several different methods are used to attach the tag to an organism.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] In fish, tags are frequently surgically implanted in the abdominal cavity.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] Surgical implantation generally results in high tag retention, therefore it is regularly used.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] Electro-immobilization with a TENS unit and chemical immobilization with compounds such as eugenol are commonly used to restrict fish movement during surgery.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] In some instances, tags are endogastrically implanted by forcing the tag down the gullet.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] Acoustic tags may also be attached externally using additional braces or tag types.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] By determining the sound's time of arrival at each hydrophone, the 3D position of the fish can be calculated.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] The hydrophone receiver picks up the sound signal and converts it to data that researchers use to plot the resulting tag positions in three dimensions, in real-time.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] Using a post processing software, such as *MarkTags*, takes that data and delivers the result, the 3D track.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] At present, acoustic tags are most commonly used to monitor fish approaching diversion and guidance structures at hydropower dams.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] Ultimately, working to improve bypass effectiveness and protect fish populations, Acoustic Tag Tracking Systems are a significant breakthrough in the preservation of migrating salmon populations.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] Acoustic tags have been employed to help public utility agencies, private firms, and state and federal agencies meet fisheries regulations as defined by the Federal Regulations and Oversight of Energy (FERC Archived 2020-06-15 at the Wayback Machine).
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] In the Laurentian Great Lakes, acoustic telemetry has addressed a variety of fishery research and management concerns through research conducted through the Great Lakes Acoustic Telemetry Observation System (GLATOS).
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] Estimates of spawning site fidelity have been made for lake trout and walleye.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] Acoustic telemetry has also been used to inform invasive species management through the use of *Judas fish*, or tagged fish used to "betray" the location or behaviors of others.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] Acoustic tags were used on sea lamprey in the Great Lakes to determine the effectiveness of traps at physical removal and to locate potential spawning locations.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] They have also been used on common carp throughout North America to identify seasonal aggregations for future exploitation and removal.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] Although incredibly valuable as a research and management tool, acoustic tags have some limitations.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] Foremost, the equipment required for acoustic telemetry (*e.g.*, tags, receivers, replacement batteries for receivers, mounting and deployment materials for receivers) can be cost-prohibitive especially in comparison to other techniques such as radio telemetry.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] For example, acoustic receivers can cost more than US$2,000 per unit while tags can range from $200 - US$1,000 per unit, depending on model.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] Additionally, acoustic tags have variable detection range depending on habitat type, tag size, and environmental conditions.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] Variability in detection or poor detection probability could ultimately influence conclusions made from data and therefore is important to account for by range testing.
[src:fish-stocks/acoustic-tag] Considerations on project scale and timeframe are necessary before implementing acoustic telemetry.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] Age class structures can be used to model population structures of many species including vertebrates, invertebrates, and vegetation.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] Factors that influence age class structures include birth rates, death rates, migration, and environmental stressors.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] These models allow for the prediction of growth or decline in a population based on current conditions or future management practices.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] Age class structures can be used to help focus management on a certain age class to obtain the desires population size outcomes.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] Individuals in a population that are within a certain age range belong to the same class.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] These age classes count age like we usually do: individuals who are less than 1 year old are considered age class 0, those who are at least one year old but not yet two are age 1, and so on.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] When individuals are sorted into age classes like this, we can describe the population's age structure - meaning how many individuals are in each age group.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] Imagine a species where no one lives past 3 years old.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] This means all individuals would be either less than 1 year old (age class 0), 2 years old (age class 1), or 3 years old (age class 2).
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] Therefore, if there are 20 individuals in total - 4 are newborns, 6 are 1-year-olds, and 10 are 2-year-olds - then the age structure would be 0.2 in age class 0, 0.3 in age class 1, and 0.5 in age class 2.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] A stable age distribution happens when birth and death rates remain the same over time.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] This creates a steady, balanced number of individuals in each age group.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] The age class structure will look like a rectangle when shown in a population pyramid, meaning there is a similar number of individuals in each age range.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] An unstable age distribution happens when birth or death rates change significantly, causing the number of individuals in each age group to shift.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] This can make the population chart look uneven - like a triangle or an inverted triangle - showing that some age groups have many more or fewer individuals than others.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] For example, when managing a population of white tail deer targeting a specific age and sex can alter the population pyramid type to either increase, decrease, or stabilize population growth.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] If you start off with a rapid growth age class structure, then targeting the juveniles who are not reproductive yet will help stabilize the population to a slower growth or no growth.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] This will make the number of juvenile females to closer the number of females who are aging out of the reproductive age.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] Targeting a specific sex will also alter the age class data.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] If looking to reduce the population then targeting hunting efforts on females will have a more impactful change.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] Removal of older individuals and males will increase the population by opening up resources for reproductive females and juveniles.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] Age can be determined by counting growth rings in fish scales, otoliths, cross-sections of fin spines for species with thick spines such as triggerfish, or teeth for a few species.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] Each method has its merits and drawbacks.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] Fish scales are easiest to obtain, but may be unreliable if scales have fallen off the fish and new ones grown in their places.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] Fin spines may be unreliable for the same reason, and most fish do not have spines of sufficient thickness for clear rings to be visible.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] Otoliths will have stayed with the fish throughout its life history, but obtaining them requires killing the fish.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] Also, otoliths often require more preparation before ageing can occur.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] An example of using age class structure to learn about a population is a regular bell curve for the population of 1-5 year-old fish with a very low population for the 3-year-olds.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] An age class structure with gaps in population size like the one described earlier implies a bad spawning year 3 years ago in that species.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] Often fish in younger age class structures have very low numbers because they were small enough to slip through the sampling nets, and may in fact have a very healthy population.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] This could skew class structure data and result in imaccurate management techniques.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] Growing evidence suggests temporal shifts in body size, often studied with respect to climate and Bergmann's rule, may be explained by shifts in the age structure of a population.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] Because individuals change in size and shape as they age, changes in age class structure can result in shifts in the morphospace of a population reflecting either a greater proportion of older (and larger) or younger (and smaller) individuals.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] Aging trees is performed through several methods, the first being to count the trees annual growth rings and the second is to calculate using the growth factor and circumference.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] After a wildfire, depending on the severity, some of the forest will experience a loss in the population of several species.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] This interference can drastically alter an age class structure.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] If the fire was low intensity and burned low to the ground killing only young trees, then the age structure would be heavily skewed towards having many older mature trees and very few young trees.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] Wild fires can alter age class structures by removing individuals in certain age classes and altering the type of population pyramid the species is experiencing.
[src:fish-stocks/age-class-structure] This shift in age class structures can also help predict how quickly the forest will rebound from the disturbance.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] An **algal bloom** or **algae bloom** is a rapid increase or accumulation in the population of algae in fresh water or marine water systems.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] It may be a benign or harmful algal bloom.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Algal bloom is often recognized by the discoloration in the water from the algae's pigments.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] The term *algae* encompasses many types of aquatic photosynthetic organisms, both macroscopic multicellular organisms like seaweed and microscopic unicellular organisms like cyanobacteria.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] *Algal bloom* commonly refers to the rapid growth of microscopic unicellular algae, not macroscopic algae.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] An example of a macroscopic algal bloom is a kelp forest.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Algal blooms are the result of a nutrient, like nitrogen or phosphorus from various sources (for example fertilizer runoff or other forms of nutrient pollution), entering the aquatic system and causing excessive growth of algae.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] An algal bloom affects the whole ecosystem.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Consequences range from benign effects, such as feeding of higher trophic levels, to more harmful effects like blocking sunlight from reaching other organisms, causing a depletion of oxygen levels in the water, and, depending on the organism, releasing toxins into the water.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Yet, algae also play a crucial role by producing about 70 % of Earth's oxygen, which supports terrestrial life.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Blooms that can injure animals or the ecology, especially those blooms where toxins are secreted by the algae, are usually called "harmful algal blooms" (HAB), and can lead to fish die-offs, cities cutting off water to residents, or states having to close fisheries.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] The process of the oversupply of nutrients leading to algae growth and oxygen depletion is called eutrophication.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Algal and bacterial blooms have persistently contributed to mass extinctions driven by global warming in the geologic past, such as during the end-Permian extinction driven by Siberian Traps volcanism and during the biotic recovery following the mass extinction (by delaying the recovery).
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] The term *algal bloom* is defined inconsistently depending on the scientific field, and can range from a "minibloom" of harmless algae to a large, harmful bloom event.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Since *algae* is a broad term including organisms of widely varying sizes, growth rates, and nutrient requirements, there is no officially recognized threshold level as to what is defined as a bloom.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Blooms are the result of a nutrient needed by the particular algae being introduced to the local aquatic system.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] This growth-limiting nutrient is typically nitrogen or phosphorus, but can also be iron, vitamins, or amino acids.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] There are several mechanisms for the addition of these nutrients to the water.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] In the open ocean and along coastlines, upwelling from both winds and topographical ocean floor features can draw nutrients to the photic, or sunlit zone of the ocean.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Along coastal regions and in freshwater systems, agricultural, city, and sewage runoff can cause algal blooms.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Algal blooms, especially large algal bloom events, can reduce the transparency of the water and can discolor it.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] The photosynthetic pigments in the algal cells, like chlorophyll and photoprotective pigments, determine the color of the algal bloom.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Depending on the organism, its pigments, and the depth in the water column, algal blooms can be green, red, brown, golden, or purple.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Bright green blooms in freshwater systems are frequently a result of cyanobacteria (colloquially known as "blue-green algae") such as *Microcystis*.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Blooms may also consist of macroalgal (non-phytoplanktonic) species.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] These blooms are recognizable by large blades of algae that may wash up onto the shoreline.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Once the nutrient is present in the water, the algae begin to grow at a much faster rate than usual.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] In a mini bloom, this fast growth benefits the whole ecosystem by providing food and nutrients for other organisms.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Of particular note are the harmful algal blooms (HABs), which are algal bloom events involving toxic or otherwise harmful phytoplankton.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Many species can cause harmful algal blooms.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Freshwater algal blooms are the result of an excess of nutrients, particularly some phosphates.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Excess nutrients may originate from fertilizers that are applied to land for agricultural or recreational purposes and may also originate from household cleaning products containing phosphorus.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] The reduction of phosphorus inputs is required to mitigate blooms that contain cyanobacteria.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] In lakes that are stratified in the summer, autumn turnover can release substantial quantities of bio-available phosphorus potentially triggering algal blooms as soon as sufficient photosynthetic light is available.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Excess nutrients can enter watersheds through water runoff.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Excess carbon and nitrogen have also been suspected as causes.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Presence of residual sodium carbonate acts as catalyst for the algae to bloom by providing dissolved carbon dioxide for enhanced photosynthesis in the presence of nutrients.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] When phosphates are introduced into water systems, higher concentrations can cause increased growth of algae and plants.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Algae tend to grow very quickly under high nutrient availability, but each alga is short-lived, and the result is a high concentration of dead organic matter which starts to decompose.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Natural decomposers present in the water begin decomposing the dead algae, consuming dissolved oxygen present in the water during the process.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] This can result in a sharp decrease in available dissolved oxygen for other aquatic life.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Without sufficient dissolved oxygen in the water, animals and plants may die off in large numbers.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Blooms may be observed in freshwater aquariums when fish are overfed and excess nutrients are not absorbed by plants.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] These are generally harmful for fish, and the situation can be corrected by changing the water in the tank and then reducing the amount of food given.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Algal blooms in freshwater systems are not always caused by human contamination and have been observed to occur naturally in both eutrophic and oligotrophic lakes.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Eutrophic lakes contain an abundance of nutrients such as nitrogen and phosphates which increase the likelihood for blooms.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Oligotrophic lakes don't contain much of these nutrients.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Oligotrophic lakes are defined by various degrees of scarcity.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] The trophic state index (TSI) measures nutrients in freshwater systems and a TSI under 30 defines oligotrophic waters.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Algal blooms in oligotrophic bodies of water have also been observed.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] This is a result of cyanobacteria which cause blooms in eutrophic lakes and oligotrophic lakes despite the latter containing a lack of natural and man-made nutrients.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] A cause for algal blooms in nutrient-lacking environments come in the form of nutrient uptake.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Cyanobacteria have evolved to have better nutrient uptake in oligotrophic waters.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Cyanobacteria utilize nitrogen and phosphates in their biological processes.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Because of this, cyanobacteria are known to be important in the nitrogen and phosphate fixing cycle in oligotrophic waters.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Cyanobacteria can fix nitrogen by accessing atmospheric nitrogen (N2) that has been dissolved into water and transforming it into nitrogen accessible to other organisms.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] This higher amount of nitrogen is then able to sustain large algae blooms in oligotrophic waters.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Cyanobacteria are able to retain high phosphorus uptake in the absence of nutrients which help their success in oligotrophic environments.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Cyanobacteria species such as *D. lemmermannii* are able to move between the hypolimnion which is rich in nutrients such as phosphates and the nutrient-poor metalimnion which lacks phosphates.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] This causes phosphates to be brought up to the metalimnion and give organisms an abundance of phosphates, exacerbating the likelihood for algal blooms.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Upwelling events happen when nutrients such as phosphates and nitrogen are moved from the nutrient dense hypolimnion to the nutrient poor metalimnion.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] This happens as result of geological processes such as seasonal overturn when lake surfaces freeze or melt, prompting mixing due to changing water densities mixing up the composition of limnion layers and mixing nutrients around the system.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] This overabundance in nutrients leads to blooms.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Turbulent storms churn the ocean in summer, adding nutrients to sunlit waters near the surface.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] This sparks a feeding frenzy each spring that gives rise to massive blooms of phytoplankton.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Tiny molecules found inside these microscopic plants harvest vital energy from sunlight through photosynthesis.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] The natural pigments, called chlorophyll, allow phytoplankton to thrive in Earth's oceans and enable scientists to monitor blooms from space.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Satellites reveal the location and abundance of phytoplankton by detecting the amount of chlorophyll present in coastal and open waters—the higher the concentration, the larger the bloom.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Observations show blooms typically last until late spring or early summer, when nutrient stocks are in decline and predatory zooplankton start to graze.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] The visualization on the left immediately below uses NASA SeaWiFS data to map bloom populations.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] The NAAMES study conducted between 2015 and 2019 investigated aspects of phytoplankton dynamics in ocean ecosystems, and how such dynamics influence atmospheric aerosols, clouds, and climate.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] In France, citizens are requested to report coloured waters through the project PHENOMER.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] This helps to understand the occurrence of marine blooms.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Wildfires can cause phytoplankton blooms via oceanic deposition of wildfire aerosols.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] A harmful algal bloom (HAB) is an algal bloom that causes negative impacts to other organisms via production of natural toxins, mechanical damage to other organisms, or by other means.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] The diversity of these HABs make them even harder to manage, and present many issues, especially to threatened coastal areas.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] HABs are often associated with large-scale marine mortality events and have been associated with various types of shellfish poisonings.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Due to their negative economic and health impacts, HABs are often carefully monitored.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] HAB has been proved to be harmful to humans.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Humans may be exposed to toxic algae by direct consuming seafood containing toxins, swimming or other activities in water, and breathing tiny droplets in the air that contain toxins.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Because human exposure can take place by consuming seafood products that contain the toxins expelled by HAB algae, food-borne diseases are present and can affect the nervous, digestive, respiratory, hepatic, dermatological, and cardiac systems in the body.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Beach users have often experienced upper respiratory diseases, eye and nose irritation, fever, and have often needed medical care in order to be treated.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Ciguatera fish poisoning (CFP) is very common from the exposure of algal blooms.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Water-borne diseases are also present as our drinking waters can be contaminated by cyanotoxins.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] If the HAB event results in a high enough concentration of algae the water may become discoloured or murky, varying in colour from purple to almost pink, normally being red or green.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Not all algal blooms are dense enough to cause water discolouration.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Historically, forecasting algal blooms relied heavily on physical water sampling and hydrodynamic modeling.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] While accurate, these methods can be resource-intensive and struggle to rapidly process highly complex, changing environmental variables.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Consequently, modern forecasting increasingly integrates remote sensing with machine learning to complement traditional physical models.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Open-science initiatives have helped accelerate these algorithmic approaches.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] For example, during the 2019 NASA International Space Apps Challenge, a student team demonstrated how convolutional neural networks could analyze satellite data to predict cyanobacteria concentrations up to a month in advance.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] In formal scientific literature, recent frameworks employ self-supervised deep learning to fuse multi-sensor and hyperspectral satellite datasets.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] These models help generate early warning systems for coastal communities and water treatment facilities.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Despite these advancements, satellite-based forecasting faces inherent limitations.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Algorithmic accuracy depends heavily on accounting for highly localized factors, such as regional eutrophication or sudden water temperature shifts.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Furthermore, optical satellite measurements are frequently obstructed by cloud cover, requiring predictive models to rely on data interpolation to bridge missing gaps.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] There are three major categories for management of algal blooms consisting of mitigation, prevention, and control.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Within mitigation, routine monitoring programs are implemented for toxins in shellfish for early warnings and an overall surveillance of the area to monitor and quantify harmful algal blooms.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] The HAB levels of the shellfish will be determined and can manage restrictions to keep contaminated shellfish off the food market.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Moving fish pens away from algal blooms is also another form of mitigation.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Within prevention, we can reduce surface runoff carrying excess nutrients by increasing the amount of permeable surfaces and vegetation.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Permeable surfaces help absorb the runoff before it can make its way into the waterway.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] We can put into place permeable streets and parking lots which help allow for the pollution from vehicles and other runoff nutrients to be soaked up and/or slowed.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Vegetation filters, absorbs, and slows the runoff which also helps to reduce the amount of excess nutrients making their way into the waterway.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Examples of planted vegetation to help reduce runoff include rain gardens, replacing grass with native plants, planting trees in yards and along waterways, and even rooftop gardens.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Farmers can reduce their impact on our waterways by planting cover crops, planting forested buffers, reducing their fertilizer use, and putting up fences to keep livestock out of streams.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Within control, there are mechanical, biological, chemical, genetic and environmental controls.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Mechanical control involves dispersing clay into the water to aggregate with the HAB leading to less of these HAB to go through the process of sedimentation.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Biological control varies largely and can be used through pheromones or releasing sterile males to reduce reproduction.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Chemical control uses toxic chemical release.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] However, it may cause problems of mortality of other non targeted organisms.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Genetic control involves genetically engineering species in their environmental tolerances and reproduction processes.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] However, there are problems of harming indigenous organisms.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] For environmental control, it can use water circulation and aeration.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Harmful algae blooms have many negative environmental impacts and is a worsening issue that is spreading in area.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] A tiny brown tide organism that was formerly restricted to the northeastern US and South Africa, is now causing massive blooms along the coast of China which is similar to that of other brown tides.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] HABs can lead to anaerobic (lack of oxygen) environments which can kill any organisms living within the water, fish poisoning, respiratory problems and illness among beach goers.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] HABs have a large effect on the Great Lakes St.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Invasive zebra and quagga mussels are positively correlated with their impact on the environment.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] These mussels increase the cycling of phosphorus which therefore increases harmful algae blooms in areas they are present.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Harmful algae blooms continue to infect water supplies at the Binational Great Lakes Basin and due to the world's recovery from the COVID-19 pandemic, solving the issue has become a low priority.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] This economical problem has become part of politics in the United States, whereas in allied countries such as Canada there is low concern.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] The impact of harmful algae blooms on the environment have a substantial effect on marine life.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] For example, in August 2024 the growth of the toxic algae, *Pseudo-nitzschia*, along California coasts were making sea lions sick and aggressive to beach goers.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Scientists claim this is a seasonal occurrence.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] The growth of *Pseudo-nitzschia* leads to the production of a dominic acid which accumulates in fishes such as sardines, anchovies, and squids.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] This directly affects the food web and the primary food source of sea lions.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Once the toxins are transferred via consumption, they can cause seizures, brain damage, and death to the animal.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] During this surge, people reported bites and unpredictable, aggressive behavior from the infected sea lions.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] In this sickened state, the sea lions are scared and act out of fear in order to protect themselves.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Pregnant sea lions are most vulnerable to toxic algae poisoning and are more likely to die from the effects.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] In recent decades, the intensity and occurrence of algae blooms has increased.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] This is primarily due to the heating of oceans and other bodies of water, which stimulates algae growth, and also extends the growing season.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] However, climate change can also result in a decrease in algae blooms, due to intense rainfall that can flush the blooms out of bodies of water.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Moreover, the distribution of algae blooms has been predicted to expand north, particularly in the North Sea, in the next century.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Alongside climate change, the increase in algae blooms can be attributed to human practices.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] In agriculture, the use of fertilizers can provide the necessary nutrients for algae growth, and enter the water cycle from surface runoff.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] The first algal bloom in the world is *Eoseira wilsonii*.
[src:fish-stocks/algal-bloom] Dating back to the Eocene, it is the only known diatom to have algal blooms found in the Horsefly Shale and Eocene Okanagan Highlands.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] When angling, the fisherman (known as the **angler**) will first throw the hook (i.e.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] "cast") to a chosen area of water (i.e. fishing ground), and then patiently wait for fish to approach and devour the hookbait.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] It is also not uncommon for the angler to scatter some loose bait (groundbait) around the target area before even casting the hook, to better attract distant fish with scents.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] If a fish has succumbed to its own feeding instinct and swallowed the baited hook (i.e.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] "bite" or "strike"), the hook point will likely pierce into and anchor itself inside the fish jaw, gullet or gill, and the fish in turn becomes firmly tethered by the fishing line.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Once the fish is hooked (often colloquially called "fish-on"), any struggles and attempts to escape will pull along the line, causing the bite indicator to signal the angler, who jerks the fishing rod back to further deepen the hook anchorage (i.e.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] "setting the hook") and then tries to retrieve the line back, pulling the fish closer in the process.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] During the line retrieval, the angler will carefully monitor the line and rod tension to avoid equipment breaking.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] With stronger and feistier fish, the angler might need to temporarily halt or even reverse the line retrieval to prolong the struggle time and tire out the fish (i.e.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] "walking" or "playing" the fish), before dragging it near enough to eventually lift it out of the water (known as "*landing*") for a successful catch.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Sometimes a hand net (or "landing net") or a long-handled hook is used to make fetching the fish easier.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Angling is the principal method of recreational fishing, but commercial fisheries also use angling methods such as longlining, trotlining or trolling.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] In many parts of the world, a fishing licence is mandated for angling and size limits apply to certain species, meaning by law, fish below and/or above a certain size range must be released alive after capture.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] The popular fish species pursued by anglers, collectively known as game fish, vary with geography.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Among the many species of saltwater fish that are angled for sport globally are billfish (swordfish, sailfish and marlin), tuna, trevally and grouper, while cod and sea bass are popular targets in Europe.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] In North America, the popular freshwater fish species include bass, northern pike/muskellunge, walleye, trout and anadromous salmon, tilapia, channel catfish and panfishes such as crappie, sunfish (e.g. bluegill) and yellow perch.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] In Europe, Asia and Australasia, freshwater anglers often pursue species such as carp, pike, bream, tench, rudd, roach, European perch, catfish and barbel, many of which are regarded as undesirable "rough fish" in North America.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] In developed countries, catch and release angling is increasingly practiced by sport fishermen in recent years to conserve the fish stocks and help maintain sustainability of the local fisheries.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Angling is not to be confused with snagging, another fishing technique that also uses line and hook to catch fish.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Snagging also inflicts far more mutilating injuries to the fish and makes it very difficult to heal and survive even if the fish is released alive or manages to escape the snag.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] A fishing rod is a long, thin stick/pole that acts as an extended lever and allows the angler to amplify line movements while luring and pulling the fish.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] It also enhances casting distance by lengthening the swing radius (compared to that of a human arm) and increasing the launch speed of the terminal tackles (the hook, bait/lure, and other co-launched attachments such as float and sinker/feeder).
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Modern rods also may come in multi-piece or telescoping forms, which are more portable and storage-friendly.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Fishing rods are categorized based on the rod's intended use.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] The type of reel and/or the fishing technique being utilized will determine which type of rod a fisherman selects.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] The design and ergonomics of each rod type optimize them for the intended method of use.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Fishing reels are manually cranked reels typically mounted onto a fishing rod, used to wind and stow fishing line when a long casting distance or a prolonged retrieval is expected.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Traditional fishing reels are essentially compact windlasses with a "direct-drive" design, while modern reels since the Industrial Revolution typically are "multiplier" reels that use internal gear trains to gain a higher rotational speed.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] The use of the hook in angling is descended, historically, from what would today be called a *gorge*.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] The word "gorge", in this context, comes from the French word meaning "throat".
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Gorges were used by ancient peoples to capture fish and animals like seal, walrus and birds.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] A gorge was a long, thin piece of bone or stone attached by its midpoint to a thin line.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] The gorge would be baited so that it would rest parallel to the lay of the line.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] When the game would swallow the bait, a tug on the line would cause the gorge to orient itself at right angles to the line, thereby sticking in the fish or animal's throat or gullet.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Gorges evolved into the modern fishing hook which is J-shaped with a loop on one end and a sharp point on the other.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Most hooks have a barb near the point to better anchor the point and prevent a fish from unhooking itself while being reeled in.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Some laws and regulations require hooks to be barbless, typically to facilitate catch and release.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] This rule is commonly implemented to protect populations of certain species, as a barbed hook could cause significant collateral lacerations (especially when it penetrates the gill) that can kill a fish even after released alive.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Fishing lines are long, ultra-thin, flexible cords that may come in monofilament or braided multifilament forms.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Traditional fishing lines are made of silk, while most modern fishing lines are made from synthetic polymers such as nylon, polyethylene, polyvinylidene fluoride ("fluorocarbon") or copolymer materials.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Important specifications for a fishing line include its material and forms, test weight, diameter, stretch, memory, abrasion resistance, UV resistance, and reflective and/or refractive visibility.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] A bite indicator is any device that can help to notify the angler that the hook has been swallowed by a fish.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] There are many types of bite indicators, the oldest and most ubiquitously used being the fishing float, a lightweight marker buoy that floats at the water surface with the hook and bait suspended below it.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] When the fish swallows the hook, the leader line between the hook and the float pulls the float deeper into the water, causing it to oscillates in and out of water in a bobbing-like fashion (hence its American English name, the "bobber").
[src:fish-stocks/angling] In colloquial usage, the word "bait" refers specifically to hookbaits, which can be further separated into three main categories: *natural baits*, *artificial baits* and *lures*.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] The choice of what bait to use is dictated mainly by the target species's diet, the habitat and weather conditions (which can alter the fish's foraging behavior), the angler's own personal preferences, and the local fishery regulations.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Using an optimal angling bait can increase the chance of catching the intended fish, while conversely using an inadequate bait will greatly reduce the success rate, especially when there are other bait fishermen nearby.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Natural baits are food items that are present within the target fish's natural diet, which are usually animals at a lower trophic level in the food web.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] A natural bait angler, with few exceptions, will use a common prey species of the target fish as a bait.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] The natural bait used may be live food (known as a *live bait*) or carcass (i.e.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] *dead bait*), and a bait improvised from grossly intact portions of a dead animal (e.g. fish head) is known as a *cutbait*.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Common natural baits for both fresh and saltwater fishing include earthworm, leech, insects and larvae, minnow, squid, prawn, crayfish, and even crabs, frogs and salamanders.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Natural baits are effective due to the real texture, odour and movements of the bait presented.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] The common earthworm is a universal live bait for freshwater angling, and grubs and maggots are also excellent bait when trout fishing.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Grasshoppers, crickets, eels and even ants are also used as bait for trout in their season, although many anglers believe that trout or salmon roe is superior to any other bait.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Crayfish, which are preyed upon by a variety of ray-finned fishes, are also commonly used as bait, either live or with only the tail meat.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] They are popular for catching catfish, largemouth bass, smallmouth bass, striped bass, perch and pike.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] However, studies had confirmed that introducing crayfish outside of their home range has led to various ecological problems of them becoming invasive species.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Transporting crayfish as live bait has also contributed to the spread of zebra mussels, which are known to attach themselves onto crayfish, in various waterways throughout Europe and North America.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] The capture, transportation and culture of bait fish can spread damaging organisms between ecosystems, endangering them.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] In 2007 several American states enacted regulations designed to slow the spread of fish diseases, including viral hemorrhagic septicemia, by bait fish.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Because of the risk of transmitting *Myxobolus cerebralis* (whirling disease), trout and salmon should not be used as bait.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Anglers may increase the possibility of contamination by emptying bait buckets into fishing venues and collecting or using bait improperly.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] The transportation of fish from one location to another can break the law and cause the introduction of fish alien to the ecosystem.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Artificial baits are edible baits that are not directly acquired via natural means, but are made from other food materials via some kind of artificial processing.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] In lakes in southern climates such as Florida, panfish such as sunfish will even take household wheat bread or pet food as bait.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] These bread bait is prepared from a small amount of bread, often moistened and softened by saliva, then squeezed into a ball of the bite size of small fish.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] These inedible, replica baits are typically called *lures* instead of baits, although expressions such as "swimbaits", "crankbaits", "jerkbaits", "spinnerbaits" and "chatterbaits" are still used when describing specific types of lures.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Many anglers prefer to fish solely using lures, as these rely more on the user's rod and reel actions to successfully attract fish, and requires frequent casting and retrieving the line, and are thus more interactive and exciting.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Lures can be broadly categorized into *hard-body* and *soft-body lures*, although hybrid lures with both hard and soft components are also common.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Soft-body lures tend to give a more flexible and realistic "swimming" posture when towed through the water, while hard-body lures usually rely on stirring up more noise and turbulences.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Some newer hard lure designs, however, are multi-jointed and can resemble soft lures in dynamics.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Soft lures are typically coupled with a single conventional fish hook or a jighead, while hard lures commonly have more than one hook (which are often treble hooks).
[src:fish-stocks/angling] When lures are used in combination with other terminal tackles (floats, sinkers, swivels, etc.) to produce sophisticated presentations, the entire lure package is known as a *rig*.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Common rigs with a soft plastic lure are the Texas Rig or the Carolina Rig.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Some fishing lures (e.g. spoons and spinnerbaits) may not even resemble any prey in looks, and may require skilled rod movements to impart an enticing presentation to the target fish, for example in jigging and topwater fishing.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Some lures, such as the flies used in fly fishing, are ultralight and even require specialized gears and techniques to be cast properly.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] In modern times, there are also lures that photically attract fish with LED illuminiation, as well as battery-powered "bionic" lures that are essentially primitive robot fish that can swim around without needing to be towed by a fishing line.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Although all angling techniques use bait, the term "bait fishing" specifically refers to those that use edible materials (e.g. worms, insects, crustaceans and smaller bait fish) as baits.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Lure fishing uses a type of artificial fake bait known as *lure*, which is usually made from inedible materials such as wood, metal and plastics.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Unlike conventional fishing baits, lures do not emit any scent and thus cannot attract fish olfactorily, but instead using prey-like appearances, movements, vibrations, bright reflections and flashy colors to attract and entice carnivorous predatory fish into mistakenly striking.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Many lures are equipped with more than one hooks to better the chance of anchoring into the fish's mouth, though some hookless lures are used to bait the fish nearer so it can be captured via other means such as spearing, netting, trapping or capturing by hand.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] In addition to rod angling, handlining, longlining and commercial trolling also employ lure fishing.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Lure fishing is a popular style of recreational fishing.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] A skilled angler can explore many possible hiding spots for fish through lure casting such as under logs and on flats.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] No bite indicator is used, and when the lure catches the attention of a game fish and successfully results in biting/swallowing of the lure, the angler can detect it by watching for splashes and feeling any vibrations, rod bending and changes in line tension.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Lure fishing also typically uses relatively lightweight fishing rods coupled with baitcasting reels or spinning reels.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Slabbing is a type of jigging that involves repetitively lifting and dropping a flat lure, usually made of 1 to 2.5 oz of lead painted to look like a baitfish (or heavy slabs of metal), through a school of actively feeding fish that the angler has located on a fishfinder.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] It is a bass fishing technique and is used on white and striped bass in the reservoirs of the southern US.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Almost all recreational angling activities involve the use of fishing rods, which is used to manipulate the movements of fishing lines and to allow farther casting of baits/lures.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Although all angling techniques use hook and line, the term "line fishing" specifically refers to those that do not involve using fishing rods.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Line fishing is also known as *rodless fishing*.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Handlining, or handline fishing, is done with a handheld fishing line baited with lures or bait fish.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Handlining is the oldest angling technique used by mankind, and can be done from boats or from the shore.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] It is used mainly to catch groundfish and squid, but smaller pelagic fish can also be caught.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Longlining, or longline fishing, is a commercial fishing technique that uses a long heavy line with a series of hundreds or even thousands of baited hooks hanging from the main line via branch lines called *snoods*.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Longlines are usually operated from specialised boats called *longliners*, which use a special winch to haul in the line and can operate in deeper waters targeting pelagic species such as swordfish, tuna, halibut and sablefish.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Droplining involves setting a longline vertically down into the water (instead of being more horizontally deployed like longlining) with a series of baited hooks.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Droplines are weighted at the bottom and have a float at the top.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] They are not usually as long as longlines and have fewer hooks, and tend to be stationary.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Trotlining uses a longline that, instead of being tethered to the water surface only at one end, are fixed at/near the surface at both ends of the longline, with hooked snood lines hanging vertically down along the main line.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Trotlines are used for catching crabs or fish (e.g. catfish), particularly across rivers.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] They can be physically set in many ways, such as tying each end to a fixed structure and span the line across the water in-between like a boom, and adjusting rest of the line with weights and floats.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Deadlining is the practice of leaving a baited fishing line in the water (with the other end fastened to the bank) and returning later (usually overnight) to check and capture any tethered fish, similar to the use of a snare trap by hunters.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Float fishing is the most common method of angling, defined by the use of a compact light buoy attached to fishing line – known as a *float* (or "*bobber*" in the United States) — as the bite indicator.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Due to buoyancy, the float remains at the water surface and suspends the baited hook at a predetermined depth.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] It can also drift in the prevailing current and carry the hook to areas of water otherwise inaccessible by casting alone.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] When the fish bites and swallows the hook, the float visually signals any forces exerted on the leader line below it, as the fisherman can then see it being pulled underwater and/or sideways.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Bottom fishing, also called *legering* in the United Kingdom, uses a weighted tackle called a *sinker* tied to the end of the fishing line to keep the baited hook close to the bottom of the water, to target groundfishes such as sucker, bream, catfish and crappie.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] The sinker can also be used to add momentum to the hook and help casting the line to a further distance.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] The method can be used both with handlining and rod fishing, and can be done both from boats and from the land.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Specialized fishing rods called "donkas" are also commonly used for bottom fishing, and a quiver tip (sometimes coupled with a jingle bell) is used instead as the bite indicator.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Some sinkers are replaced by *feeders*, which is designed to contain and release groundbaits to help attract fish towards the hook.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Trolling is a method of fishing where one or more fishing lines, baited with lures or bait fish, are drawn through the water at a consistent, low speed.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Rod trolling is a technique in which fishing rods function as improvised outriggers to tow the baits/lures through the water, usually behind or beside a moving boat with the rod fixated to the gunwale.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] It can also be done by very slowly winding the line in (like finesse lure fishing) or even sweeping the line sideways, with the angler operating the rod from a static position (e.g. atop a jetty, pier or bridge).
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Rodless trolling is a technique in which one or more baited lines are drawn through the water behind a slow moving fishing boat.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] The boat is usually equipped with outriggers, downriggers and trolling motors.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Rodless trolling is typically used in commercial fishing, and is used to catch economic pelagic fish such as mackerel and kingfish.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] "pulled") is a Filipino traditional shoreline trolling, uniquely using baited hooks tied to a laterally flattened float called *palyaw*, which is shaped like a small outrigger boat, a catamaran or a fish.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] A longline is attached to the float, and set unto the water's edge and dragged by someone running or walking along the beach.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] The combination of the water resistance and the diagonal pull forces the float outwards into deeper waters, like a kite.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Once the line reaches its maximum line length, it moves rapidly parallel to the person pulling it along the beach, and is pulled back to the shore intermittently to check for catches.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] It is also called subid-subid, sibid-sibid, paguyod, pahinas, hilada, or saliwsiw, among other names, in other Philippine languages.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Drift fishing is a fishing technique in which the line is not actively reeled and the bait/lure is allowed to drift and react freely to the turbulences in the water current, much like how a tethered kite would behave in a wind gust.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] It is usually done from an unpowered boat in faster-flowing waters.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Laws and regulations managing angling vary greatly, often regionally, within countries.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] These commonly include permits (licences), closed periods (seasons) where specific species are unavailable for harvest, restrictions on gear types, and quotas.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Laws generally prohibit catching fish with hooks other than in the mouth (i.e. snagging, or "foul hooking" and "jagging") or the use of nets and hand hooks other than as an aid in landing a captured fish.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Some species, such as bait fish, may be taken with nets, and a few for food.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Sometimes, non-sport fish are considered of lesser value and it may be permissible to take them by methods like snagging, bow and arrow or spearing, none of which fall under the definition of angling since they do not rely upon the use of a hook and line.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Fishing seasons are set by countries or localities to indicate what kinds of fish may be caught during sport fishing (also known as angling) for a certain period of time.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Fishing seasons are enforced (usually by water police) to maintain ecological balance and to protect species of fish during their spawning period during which they are easier to catch and more physiologically vulnerable.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Slot limits prohibit the harvest of fish where the measured lengths (from the snout to the end of the tail fin) fall within a protected interval.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] These are put in action to help protect certain fish (usually juvenile) in a given area.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] They generally require anglers to release captured fish if they fall within a given size range, allowing anglers to keep only smaller (though rare) or larger fish.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Slot limits vary from water to water depending on what local officials believe would produce the best outcome for managing fish populations.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Individual fishing quota (IFQ), also known as individual transferable quota (ITQ), is a kind of *catch share* that sets a species-specific total allowable catch (TAC), typically by weight and for a given time period.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] A dedicated portion of the TAC (called "quota share") is then allocated to individual fishermen, and can typically be transferable (i.e. bought, sold or leased).
[src:fish-stocks/angling] As of 2008, 148 major fisheries (generally, a single species in a single fishing ground) around the world had adopted some variant of this approach, along with approximately 100 smaller fisheries in individual countries.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Approximately 10% of the marine harvest was managed by ITQs as of 2008.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] The minimum landing size (MLS) is the smallest fish measurement at which it is legal for the fisherman to keep a captured fish.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] The MLS depends on the species of fish, and allowed sizes also vary around the world, as they are legal definitions which are defined by the local regulatory authority.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] The idea behind this limitation is that only the older, more mature adult fish get taken, leaving growing juveniles behind to continue breeding and propagating their species.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] There is some criticism of this legal requirement, however, as it applies artificial selection pressure to the fish population (see Fisheries-induced evolution) unless the anglers voluntarily practise catch and release indiscriminate of sizes.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] As larger fish (whose survival has been more successful so far) get taken out of the population, the genes for larger size are reduced or removed from the gene pool, while fish that mature at a smaller size survive longer to continue breeding, and the average size of fish stock shrinks over time.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] This has led to a collapse in the amount of catchable fish in some fisheries.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Although most anglers keep their catch for consumption, catch and release fishing is increasingly practiced, especially by fly anglers.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] The general principle is that releasing fish allows them to survive, thus avoiding unintended depletion of the population.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] For species such as marlin, muskellunge, and bass, there is a cultural taboo among anglers against taking them for food.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] In many parts of the world, size limits apply to certain species, meaning fish below a certain size must, by law, be released.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] It is generally believed that larger fish have a greater breeding potential.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Some fisheries have a slot limit that allows the taking of smaller and larger fish, but requiring that intermediate sized fish be released.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] It is generally accepted that this management approach will help the fishery create a number of large, trophy-sized fish.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] In smaller fisheries that are heavily fished, catch and release is the only way to ensure that catchable fish will be available from year to year.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] The practice of catch and release is criticised by some who consider it unethical to inflict pain upon a fish for purposes of sport.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Some of those who object to releasing fish do not object to killing fish for food.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Adherents of catch and release dispute this charge, pointing out that fish commonly feed on hard and spiky prey items, and as such can be expected to have tough mouths, and also that some fish will re-take a lure they have just been hooked on, a behaviour that is unlikely if hooking were painful.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Opponents of catch and release fishing would find it preferable to ban or to severely restrict angling.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] On the other hand, proponents state that catch-and-release is necessary for many fisheries to remain sustainable, is a practice that generally has high survival rates, and consider the banning of angling as not reasonable or necessary.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] In some jurisdictions, in the Canadian province of Manitoba, for example, catch and release is mandatory for some species such as brook trout.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Many of the jurisdictions which mandate the live release of sport fish also require the use of artificial lures and barbless hooks to minimise the chance of injury to fish.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Mandatory catch and release also exists in the Republic of Ireland where it was introduced as a conservation measure to prevent the decline of Atlantic salmon stocks on some rivers.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] In Switzerland, catch and release fishing is considered inhumane and was banned in September 2008.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Barbless hooks, which can be created from a standard hook by removing the barb with pliers or can be bought, are sometimes resisted by anglers because they believe that increased fish escapes.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Barbless hooks reduce handling time, thereby increasing survival.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Concentrating on keeping the line taut while fighting fish, using recurved point or "triple grip" style hooks on lures, and equipping lures that do not have them with split rings can significantly reduce escapement.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Angling is also practiced in fishing tournaments, where contestants compete for prizes based on the total length or weight of a fish, usually of a pre-determined species, caught within a specified time.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] These contests originated as local fishing contests and have evolved to include large competitive circuits, with professional anglers that are supported by commercial endorsements.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Professional anglers may gain cash prizes for placing well in tournaments.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Similar competitive fishing exists at the amateur level with fishing derbies.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] In general, derbies can be distinguished from tournaments; derbies normally require fish to be killed, as opposed to tournaments, where points are normally deducted if fish can not be released alive.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] A ten-year-long survey of US fishing club members, completed in 1997, indicated that motivations for recreational angling have shifted from personal leisure, outdoor exercise, experiencing nature and thrill of the catch, to the importance of family time and social bonding via recreational fishing.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Anglers with higher family incomes went fishing more frequently and were less concerned about obtaining fish as food.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] A German study indicated that satisfaction derived from angling was not dependent on the actual catch, but depended more on the angler's expectations of the experience.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] A 2006 study by the Louisiana Department of Wildlife and Fisheries tracked the motivations of anglers on the Red River.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Among the most often stated responses were the fun of catching fish, the experience, to catch a lot of fish or a very large fish, for challenge, and adventure.
[src:fish-stocks/angling] Use as food was not investigated as a motive.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Aquaculture can also be defined as the breeding, growing, and harvesting of fish and other aquatic plants, also known as farming in water.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] It is an environmental source of food and commercial products that help to improve healthier habitats and are used to reconstruct the population of endangered aquatic species.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Technology has increased the growth of fish in coastal marine waters and open oceans due to the increased demand for seafood.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Aquaculture can be conducted in completely artificial facilities built on land (onshore aquaculture), as in the case of fish tank, ponds, aquaponics or raceways, where the living conditions rely on human control such as water quality (oxygen), feed or temperature.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] According to the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO), aquaculture "is understood to mean the farming of aquatic organisms including fish, molluscs, crustaceans and aquatic plants.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Farming implies some form of intervention in the rearing process to enhance production, such as regular stocking, feeding, protection from predators, etc.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Farming also implies individual or corporate ownership of the stock being cultivated." The reported output from global aquaculture operations in 2019 was over 120 million tonnes valued at US$274 billion, by 2022, it had risen to 130.9 million tonnes, valued at USD 312.8 billion.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] However, there are issues with the reliability of the reported figures.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Further, in current aquaculture practice, products from several kilograms of wild fish are used to produce one kilogram of a piscivorous fish like salmon.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Plant and insect-based feeds are also being developed to help reduce wild fish being used for aquaculture feed.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Particular kinds of aquaculture include fish farming, shrimp farming, oyster farming, mariculture, pisciculture, algaculture (such as seaweed farming), and the cultivation of ornamental fish.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Particular methods include aquaponics and integrated multi-trophic aquaculture, both of which integrate fish farming and aquatic plant farming.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The FAO describes aquaculture as one of the industries most directly affected by climate change and its impacts.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Some forms of aquaculture have negative impacts on the environment, such as through nutrient pollution or disease transfer to wild populations.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Harvest stagnation in wild fisheries and overexploitation of popular marine species, combined with a growing demand for high-quality protein, encouraged aquaculturists to domesticate other marine species.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] At the outset of modern aquaculture, many were optimistic that a "Blue Revolution" could take place in aquaculture, just as the Green Revolution of the 20th century had revolutionized agriculture.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Although land animals had long been domesticated, most seafood species were still caught from the wild.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] About 430 (97%) of the species cultured as of 2007 were domesticated during the 20th and 21st centuries, of which an estimated 106 came in the decade to 2007.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Given the long-term importance of agriculture, to date, only 0.08% of known land plant species and 0.0002% of known land animal species have been domesticated, compared with 0.17% of known marine plant species and 0.13% of known marine animal species.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Domestication typically involves about a decade of scientific research.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Domesticating aquatic species involves fewer risks to humans than do land animals, which took a large toll in human lives.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Most major human diseases originated in domesticated animals, including diseases such as smallpox and diphtheria, that like most infectious diseases, move to humans from animals.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] No human pathogens of comparable virulence have yet emerged from marine species.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In 2024 aquaculture production was concentrated in Asia which accounted for around 89% of global aquatic animal aquaculture production, followed by Latin America and the Caribbean (3%), Europe (2%), Africa (2%), Northern America (0.4%) and Oceania (0.2%).
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The top five countries together produced 82% of the total output; China, Indonesia, India, Viet Nam and Bangladesh.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Freshwater systems dominate aquaculture production of aquatic animals, accounting for 64 million tonnes (63%), compared to 38 million tonnes (37%) from marine and coastal systems.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Biological control methods to manage parasites are already being used, such as cleaner fish (e.g. lumpsuckers and wrasse) to control sea lice populations in salmon farming.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Models are being used to help with spatial planning and siting of fish farms in order to minimize impact.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The decline in wild fish stocks has increased the demand for farmed fish.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] However, finding alternative sources of protein and oil for fish feed is necessary so the aquaculture industry can grow sustainably; otherwise, it represents a great risk for the over-exploitation of forage fish.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Aquaculture production now exceeds capture fishery production and together the relative GDP contribution has ranged from 0.01 to 10%.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Singling out aquaculture's relative contribution to GDP, however, is not easily derived due to lack of data.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Another recent issue following the banning in 2008 of organotins by the International Maritime Organization is the need to find environmentally friendly, but still effective, compounds with antifouling effects.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Many new natural compounds are discovered every year, but producing them on a large enough scale for commercial purposes is almost impossible.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] It is highly probable that future developments in this field will rely on microorganisms, but greater funding and further research is needed to overcome the lack of knowledge in this field.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Microalgae, also referred to as phytoplankton, microphytes, or planktonic algae, constitute the majority of cultivated algae.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Macroalgae commonly known as seaweed also have many commercial and industrial uses, but due to their size and specific requirements, they are not easily cultivated on a large scale and are most often taken in the wild.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In 2016, aquaculture was the source of 96.5 percent by volume of the total 31.2 million tonnes of wild-collected and cultivated aquatic plants combined.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Global production of farmed aquatic plants, overwhelmingly dominated by seaweeds, grew in output volume from 13.5 million tonnes in 1995 to just over 30 million tonnes in 2016.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Seaweed farming or kelp farming is the practice of cultivating and harvesting seaweed.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In its simplest form farmers gather from natural beds, while at the other extreme farmers fully control the crop's life cycle.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The seven most cultivated taxa are *Eucheuma* spp., *Kappaphycus alvarezii*, *Gracilaria* spp., *Saccharina japonica*, *Undaria pinnatifida*, *Pyropia* spp., and *Sargassum fusiforme*.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] *Eucheuma* and *K. alvarezii* are attractive for carrageenan (a gelling agent); *Gracilaria* is farmed for agar; the rest are eaten after limited processing.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Seaweeds are different from mangroves and seagrasses, as they are photosynthetic algal organisms and are non-flowering.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The largest seaweed-producing countries as of 2022 are China (58.62%) and Indonesia (28.6%); followed by South Korea (5.09%) and the Philippines (4.19%).
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Seaweed farming has frequently been developed to improve economic conditions and to reduce fishing pressure.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that world production in 2019 was over 35 million tonnes.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] North America produced some 23,000 tonnes of wet seaweed.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Alaska, Maine, France, and Norway each more than doubled their seaweed production since 2018*.* As of 2019, seaweed represented 30% of marine aquaculture.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In 2023, the global seaweed extract market was valued at $16.5 billion, with strong projected growth.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Seaweed farming is a carbon negative crop, with a high potential for climate change mitigation.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The IPCC Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate recommends "further research attention" as a mitigation tactic.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] World Wildlife Fund, Oceans 2050, and The Nature Conservancy publicly support expanded seaweed cultivation.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The farming of fish is the most common form of aquaculture.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] It involves raising fish commercially in tanks, fish ponds, or ocean enclosures, usually for food.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] A facility that releases juvenile fish into the wild for recreational fishing or to supplement a species' natural numbers is generally referred to as a fish hatchery.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Worldwide, the most important fish species used in fish farming are, in order, carp, salmon, tilapia, and catfish.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In the Mediterranean, young bluefin tuna are netted at sea and towed slowly towards the shore.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] They are then interned in offshore pens (sometimes made from floating HDPE pipe) where they are further grown for the market.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In 2009, researchers in Australia managed for the first time to coax southern bluefin tuna to breed in landlocked tanks.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Southern bluefin tuna are also caught in the wild and fattened in grow-out sea cages in southern Spencer Gulf, South Australia.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] A similar process is used in the salmon-farming section of this industry; juveniles are taken from hatcheries and a variety of methods are used to aid them in their maturation.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] For example, as stated above, some of the most important fish species in the industry, salmon, can be grown using a cage system.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] This is done by having netted cages, preferably in open water that has a strong flow, and feeding the salmon a special food mixture that aids their growth.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] This process allows for year-round growth of the fish, thus a higher harvest during the correct seasons.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] An additional method, known sometimes as sea ranching, has also been used within the industry.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Sea ranching involves raising fish in a hatchery for a brief time and then releasing them into marine waters for further development, whereupon the fish are recaptured when they have matured.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Commercial shrimp farming began in the 1970s, and production grew steeply thereafter.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Global production reached more than 1.6 million tonnes in 2003, worth about US$9 billion.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] About 75% of farmed shrimp is produced in Asia, in particular in China and Thailand.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The other 25% is produced mainly in Latin America, where Brazil is the largest producer.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Shrimp farming has changed from its traditional, small-scale form in Southeast Asia into a global industry.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Technological advances have led to ever higher densities per unit area, and broodstock is shipped worldwide.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Virtually all farmed shrimp are penaeids (i.e., shrimp of the family Penaeidae), and just two species of shrimp, the Pacific white shrimp and the giant tiger prawn, account for about 80% of all farmed shrimp.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] These industrial monocultures are very susceptible to disease, which has decimated shrimp populations across entire regions.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Increasing ecological problems, repeated disease outbreaks, and pressure and criticism from both nongovernmental organizations and consumer countries led to changes in the industry in the late 1990s and generally stronger regulations.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In 1999, governments, industry representatives, and environmental organizations initiated a program aimed at developing and promoting more sustainable farming practices through the Seafood Watch program.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Freshwater prawn farming shares many characteristics with, including many problems with, marine shrimp farming.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Unique problems are introduced by the developmental lifecycle of the main species, the giant river prawn.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The global annual production of freshwater prawns (excluding crayfish and crabs) in 2007 was about 460,000 tonnes, exceeding 1.86 billion dollars.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Additionally, China produced about 370,000 tonnes of Chinese river crab.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In addition astaciculture is the freshwater farming of crayfish (mostly in the US, Australia, and Europe).
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Aquacultured shellfish include various oyster, mussel, and clam species.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] These bivalves are filter and/or deposit feeders, which rely on ambient primary production rather than inputs of fish or other feed.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] As such, shellfish aquaculture is generally perceived as benign or even beneficial.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Depending on the species and local conditions, bivalve molluscs are either grown on the beach, on longlines, or suspended from rafts and harvested by hand or by dredging.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In May 2017 a Belgian consortium installed the first of two trial mussel farms on a wind farm in the North Sea.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Abalone farming began in the late 1950s and early 1960s in Japan and China.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Since the mid-1990s, this industry has become increasingly successful.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Overfishing and poaching have reduced wild populations to the extent that farmed abalone now supplies most abalone meat.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Sustainably farmed molluscs can be certified by Seafood Watch and other organizations, including the World Wildlife Fund (WWF).
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] WWF initiated the "Aquaculture Dialogues" in 2004 to develop measurable and performance-based standards for responsibly farmed seafood.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In 2009, WWF co-founded the Aquaculture Stewardship Council with the Dutch Sustainable Trade Initiative to manage the global standards and certification programs.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] After trials in 2012, a commercial "sea ranch" was set up in Flinders Bay, Western Australia, to raise abalone.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The ranch is based on an artificial reef made up of 5000 (As of April 2016) separate concrete units called *abitats* (abalone habitats).
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The 900 kg abitats can host 400 abalone each.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The reef is seeded with young abalone from an onshore hatchery.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The abalone feed on seaweed that has grown naturally on the habitats, with the ecosystem enrichment of the bay also resulting in growing numbers of dhufish, pink snapper, wrasse, and Samson fish, among other species.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Brad Adams, from the company, has emphasised the similarity to wild abalone and the difference from shore-based aquaculture.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Other groups include aquatic reptiles, amphibians, and miscellaneous invertebrates, such as echinoderms and jellyfish.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] They are separately graphed at the top right of this section, since they do not contribute enough volume to show clearly on the main graph.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Commercially harvested echinoderms include sea cucumbers and sea urchins.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In China, sea cucumbers are farmed in artificial ponds as large as 400 hectares (1,000 acres).
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Global fish production peaked at about 171 million tonnes in 2016, with aquaculture representing 47 percent of the total and 53 percent if non-food uses (including reduction to fishmeal and fish oil) are excluded.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] With capture fishery production relatively static since the late 1980s, aquaculture has been responsible for the continuing growth in the supply of fish for human consumption.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Global aquaculture production (including aquatic plants) in 2016 was 110.2 million tonnes, with the first-sale value estimated at US$244 billion.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Three years later, in 2019 the reported output from global aquaculture operations was over 120 million tonnes valued at US$274 billion and by 2022 it had reached 130.9 million tonnes, valued at USD 312.8 billion.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] For the first time, aquaculture surpassed capture fisheries in aquatic animal production with 94.4 million tonnes, representing 51 percent of the world total and a record 57 percent of the production destined for human consumption.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In 2024 aquaculture produced 103 million tonnes of aquatic animals, an all-time record, equivalent to 53% ofglobal aquatic animal output, and over 59% of aquatic animal foods for human consumption.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In 2022 most aquaculture workers were in Asia (95%), followed by Africa (3%) and Latin America and the Caribbean (2%).
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The contribution of aquaculture to the global production of capture fisheries and aquaculture combined has risen continuously, reaching 46.8 percent in 2016, up from 25.7 percent in 2000.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] With 5.8 percent annual growth rate during the period 2001–2016, aquaculture continues to grow faster than other major food production sectors, but it no longer has the high annual growth rates experienced in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In 2012, the total world production of fisheries was 158 million tonnes, of which aquaculture contributed 66.6 million tonnes, about 42%.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The growth rate of worldwide aquaculture has been sustained and rapid, averaging about 8% per year for over 30 years, while the take from wild fisheries has been essentially flat for the last decade.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The aquaculture market reached $86 billion in 2009.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Aquaculture is an especially important economic activity in China.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Between 1980 and 1997, the Chinese Bureau of Fisheries reports, aquaculture harvests grew at an annual rate of 16.7%, jumping from 1.9 million tonnes to nearly 23 million tonnes.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In 2005, China accounted for 70% of world production.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Aquaculture is also currently one of the fastest-growing areas of food production in the U.S.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] About 90% of all U.S. shrimp consumption is farmed and imported.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In recent years, salmon aquaculture has become a major export in southern Chile, especially in Puerto Montt, Chile's fastest-growing city.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] A United Nations report titled *The State of the World Fisheries and Aquaculture* released in May 2014 maintained fisheries and aquaculture support the livelihoods of some 60 million people in Asia and Africa.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] FAO estimates that in 2016, overall, women accounted for nearly 14 percent of all people directly engaged in the fisheries and aquaculture primary sector.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In 2021, global fish production reached 182 million tonnes, with approximately equal amounts coming from capture (91.2 million tonnes) and aquaculture (90.9 million tonnes).
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Aquaculture has experienced rapid growth in recent decades, increasing almost sevenfold from 1990 to 2021.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] China overwhelmingly dominates the world in reported aquaculture output, reporting a total output which is double that of the rest of the world put together.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] However, there are some historical issues with the accuracy of China's returns.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In 2001, scientists Reg Watson and Daniel Pauly expressed concerns that China was over reporting its catch from wild fisheries in the 1990s.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] They said that made it appear that the global catch since 1988 was increasing annually by 300,000 tonnes, whereas it was really shrinking annually by 350,000 tonnes.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Watson and Pauly suggested this may have been related to Chinese policies where state entities that monitored the economy were also tasked with increasing output.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Also, until more recently, the promotion of Chinese officials was based on production increases from their own areas.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The official Xinhua News Agency quoted Yang Jian, director general of the Agriculture Ministry's Bureau of Fisheries, as saying that China's figures were "basically correct".
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] However, the FAO accepted there were issues with the reliability of China's statistical returns, and for a period treated data from China, including the aquaculture data, apart from the rest of the world.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] are one of the dominant fishes in freshwater aquaculture.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Mariculture is the cultivation of marine organisms in seawater, variously in sheltered coastal waters ("inshore"), open ocean ("offshore"), and on land ("onshore").
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Farmed species include algae (from microalgae (such as phytoplankton) to macroalgae (such as seaweed); shellfish (such as shrimp), lobster, oysters), and clams, and marine finfish.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Channel catfish (*Ictalurus punctatus*), hard clams (*Mercenaria mercenaria*) and Atlantic salmon (*Salmo salar*) are prominent in the U.S. mariculture.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Mariculture may consist of raising the organisms on or in artificial enclosures such as in floating netted enclosures for salmon, and on racks or in floating cages for oysters.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In the case of enclosed salmon, they are fed by the operators; oysters on racks filter feed on naturally available food.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Abalone have been farmed on an artificial reef consuming seaweed which grows naturally on the reef units.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Integrated multi-trophic aquaculture (IMTA) is a practice in which the byproducts (wastes) from one species are recycled to become inputs (fertilizers, food) for another.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] "Multi-trophic" refers to the incorporation of species from different trophic or nutritional levels in the same system.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] This is one potential distinction from the age-old practice of aquatic polyculture, which could simply be the co-culture of different fish species from the same trophic level.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In this case, these organisms may all share the same biological and chemical processes, with few synergistic benefits, which could potentially lead to significant shifts in the ecosystem.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Some traditional polyculture systems may, in fact, incorporate a greater diversity of species, occupying several niches, as extensive cultures (low intensity, low management) within the same pond.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] A working IMTA system can result in greater total production based on mutual benefits to the co-cultured species and improved ecosystem health, even if the production of individual species is lower than in a monoculture over a short-term period.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Sometimes the term "integrated aquaculture" is used to describe the integration of monocultures through water transfer.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] For all intents and purposes, the terms "IMTA" and "integrated aquaculture" differ only in their degree of descriptiveness.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Aquaponics, fractionated aquaculture, integrated agriculture-aquaculture systems, integrated peri-urban-aquaculture systems, and integrated fisheries-aquaculture systems are other variations of the IMTA concept.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Urban aquaculture is aquaculture of fish, shellfish, and marine plants in rivers, ponds, lakes, canals located within an urban environment.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Urban aquaculture systems can be associated with a multitude of different production locations, species used, environment, and production intensity.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The use of urban aquaculture has increased over the last several years as societies continue to urbanise and demand for food in urban environments increases.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Methods of production include recirculating systems; land-based culture systems; multifunctional wetlands; ponds, borrow pits and lakes; cages and culture-based fisheries.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Most production in urban environments will include either extensive (productivity is based solely on natural runoff) or intensive (tanks and cages of monoculture production), compared to aquaculture in general, which is normally semi-intensive.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Various materials, including nylon, polyester, polypropylene, polyethylene, plastic-coated welded wire, rubber, patented rope products (Spectra, Thorn-D, Dyneema), galvanized steel and copper are used for netting in aquaculture fish enclosures around the world.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] All of these materials are selected for a variety of reasons, including design feasibility, material strength, cost, and corrosion resistance.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] By inhibiting microbial growth, copper alloy aquaculture cages avoid costly net changes that are necessary with other materials.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The resistance of organism growth on copper alloy nets also provides a cleaner and healthier environment for farmed fish to grow and thrive.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Uncrewed vessels, like ROVs and AUVs, are now being used in aquaculture in various ways, such as site planning, cage or net inspection, environmental monitoring, disaster assessment, and risk reduction.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The use of uncrewed vessels aims to increase safety, efficiency, and accuracy of aquaculture operations.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Aquaculture is a multi-million-dollar business that relies on net and cage maintenance.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Inspections used to be conducted by divers manually inspecting the nets, but uncrewed vessels are now being used to conduct faster and more efficient inspections.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Recent advances in computer vision have further improved automated monitoring, with vision-language models capable of identifying and classifying multiple fish species in underwater environments using temporally aggregated features.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Biofloc technology is also used to simultaneously improve water quality and generate bacterial biomass as food for the cultured animals.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] If performed without consideration for potential local environmental impacts, aquaculture in inland waters can result in more environmental damage than wild fisheries, though with less waste produced per kg on a global scale.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] If non-local live feeds are used, aquaculture may introduce exotic plants or animals with disastrous effects.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Improvements in methods resulting from advances in research and the availability of commercial feeds has reduced some of these concerns since their greater prevalence in the 1990s and 2000s .
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Fish waste is organic and composed of nutrients necessary in all components of aquatic food webs.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In-ocean aquaculture often produces much higher than normal fish waste concentrations.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The waste collects on the ocean bottom, damaging or eliminating bottom-dwelling life.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Waste can also decrease dissolved oxygen levels in the water column, putting further pressure on wild animals.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] An alternative model to food being added to the ecosystem, is the installation of artificial reef structures to increase the habitat niches available, without the need to add any more than ambient feed and nutrient.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] This has been used in the "ranching" of abalone in Western Australia.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Some carnivorous and omnivorous farmed fish species are fed wild forage fish.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Although carnivorous farmed fish represented only 13 percent of aquaculture production by weight in 2000, they represented 34 percent of aquaculture production by value.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Farming of carnivorous species like salmon and shrimp leads to a high demand for forage fish to match the nutrition they get in the wild.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] To satisfy this requirement, more than 50 percent of the world fish oil production is fed to farmed salmon.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Farmed salmon consume more wild fish than they generate as a final product, although the efficiency of production is improving.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] To produce one kilograms of farmed salmon, products from several kilograms of wild fish are fed to them – this can be described as the "fish-in-fish-out" (FIFO) ratio.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In 1995, salmon had a FIFO ratio of 7.5 (meaning 7.5 kilograms of wild fish feed were required to produce one kilogram of salmon); by 2006 the ratio had fallen to 4.9.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Additionally, a growing share of fish oil and fishmeal come from residues (byproducts of fish processing), rather than dedicated whole fish.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In 2012, 34 percent of fish oil and 28 percent of fishmeal came from residues.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Fishmeal and oil from residues instead of whole fish have a different composition with more ash and less protein, which may limit its potential use for aquaculture.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] As the salmon farming industry expands, it requires more wild forage fish for feed, at a time when seventy-five percent of the world's monitored fisheries are already near to or have exceeded their maximum sustainable yield.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The industrial-scale extraction of wild forage fish for salmon farming then impacts the survivability of the wild predator fish who rely on them for food.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] An important step in reducing the impact of aquaculture on wild fish is shifting carnivorous species to plant-based feeds.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Salmon feeds, for example, have gone from containing only fishmeal and oil to containing 40 percent plant protein.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The USDA has also experimented with using grain-based feeds for farmed trout.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] When properly formulated (and often mixed with fishmeal or oil), plant-based feeds can provide proper nutrition and similar growth rates in carnivorous farmed fish.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Another impact aquaculture production can have on wild fish is the risk of fish escaping from coastal pens, where they can interbreed with their wild counterparts, diluting wild genetic stocks.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Escaped fish can become invasive, out-competing native species.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] As with the farming of terrestrial animals, social attitudes influence the need for humane practices and regulations in farmed marine animals.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Under the guidelines advised by the Farm Animal Welfare Council good animal welfare means both fitness and a sense of well-being in the animal's physical and mental state.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The controversial issue in aquaculture is whether fish and farmed marine invertebrates are actually sentient, or have the perception and awareness to experience suffering.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Although no evidence of this has been found in marine invertebrates, recent studies conclude that fish do have the necessary receptors (nociceptors) to sense noxious stimuli and so are likely to experience states of pain, fear and stress.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Consequently, welfare in aquaculture is directed at vertebrates, finfish in particular.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Welfare in aquaculture can be impacted by a number of issues such as stocking densities, behavioural interactions, disease and parasitism.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] A major problem in determining the cause of impaired welfare is that these issues are often all interrelated and influence each other at different times.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Optimal stocking density is often defined by the carrying capacity of the stocked environment and the amount of individual space needed by the fish, which is very species specific.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Although behavioural interactions such as shoaling may mean that high stocking densities are beneficial to some species, in many cultured species high stocking densities may be of concern.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Crowding can constrain normal swimming behaviour, as well as increase aggressive and competitive behaviours such as cannibalism, feed competition, territoriality and dominance/subordination hierarchies.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] This potentially increases the risk of tissue damage due to abrasion from fish-to-fish contact or fish-to-cage contact.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Fish can suffer reductions in food intake and food conversion efficiency.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In addition, high stocking densities can result in water flow being insufficient, creating inadequate oxygen supply and waste product removal.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Dissolved oxygen is essential for fish respiration and concentrations below critical levels can induce stress and even lead to asphyxiation.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Ammonia, a nitrogen excretion product, is highly toxic to fish at accumulated levels, particularly when oxygen concentrations are low.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Many of these interactions and effects cause stress in the fish, which can be a major factor in facilitating fish disease.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] For many parasites, infestation depends on the host's degree of mobility, the density of the host population and vulnerability of the host's defence system.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Sea lice are the primary parasitic problem for finfish in aquaculture, high numbers causing widespread skin erosion and haemorrhaging, gill congestion, and increased mucus production.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] There are also a number of prominent viral and bacterial pathogens that can have severe effects on internal organs and nervous systems.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The key to improving welfare of marine cultured organisms is to reduce stress to a minimum, as prolonged or repeated stress can cause a range of adverse effects.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Attempts to minimise stress can occur throughout the culture process.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Understanding and providing required environmental enrichment can be vital for reducing stress and benefit aquaculture objects such as improved growth body condition and reduced damage from aggression.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] During grow-out it is important to keep stocking densities at appropriate levels specific to each species, as well as separating size classes and grading to reduce aggressive behavioural interactions.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Keeping nets and cages clean can assist positive water flow to reduce the risk of water degradation.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Not surprisingly disease and parasitism can have a major effect on fish welfare and it is important for farmers not only to manage infected stock but also to apply disease prevention measures.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Prevention methods, such as vaccination, can also induce stress because of the extra handling and injection.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Other methods include adding antibiotics to feed, adding chemicals into water for treatment baths and biological control, such as using cleaner wrasse to remove lice from farmed salmon.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Many steps are involved in transport, including capture, food deprivation to reduce faecal contamination of transport water, transfer to transport vehicle via nets or pumps, plus transport and transfer to the delivery location.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] During transport water needs to be maintained to a high quality, with regulated temperature, sufficient oxygen and minimal waste products.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In some cases anaesthetics may be used in small doses to calm fish before transport.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Aquaculture is sometimes part of an environmental rehabilitation program or as an aid in conserving endangered species.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Aquaculture is becoming a significant threat to coastal ecosystems.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] About 20 percent of mangrove forests have been destroyed since 1980, partly due to shrimp farming.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] An extended cost–benefit analysis of the total economic value of shrimp aquaculture built on mangrove ecosystems found that the external costs were much higher than the external benefits.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Over four decades, 269,000 hectares (660,000 acres) of Indonesian mangroves have been converted to shrimp farms.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Most of these farms are abandoned within a decade because of the toxin build-up and nutrient loss.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Salmon farms are typically sited in pristine coastal ecosystems which they then pollute.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] A farm with 200,000 salmon discharges more fecal waste than a city of 60,000 people.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] This waste is discharged directly into the surrounding aquatic environment, untreated, often containing antibiotics and pesticides." There is also an accumulation of heavy metals on the benthos (seafloor) near the salmon farms, particularly copper and zinc.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In 2016, mass fish kill events impacted salmon farmers along Chile's coast and the wider ecology.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Increases in aquaculture production and its associated effluent were considered to be possible contributing factors to fish and molluscan mortality.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Sea cage aquaculture is responsible for nutrient enrichment of the waters in which they are established.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] This results from fish wastes and uneaten feed inputs.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Elements of most concern are nitrogen and phosphorus which can promote algal growth, including harmful algal blooms which can be toxic to fish.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Flushing times, current speeds, distance from the shore and water depth are important considerations when locating sea cages in order to minimize the impacts of nutrient enrichment on coastal ecosystems.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The extent of the effects of pollution from sea-cage aquaculture varies depending on where the cages are located, which species are kept, how densely cages are stocked and what the fish are fed.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Important species-specific variables include the species' food conversion ratio (FCR) and nitrogen retention.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Whole-lake experiments carried out at the Experimental Lakes Area in Ontario, Canada, have displayed the potential for cage aquaculture to source numerous changes in freshwater ecosystems.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Following the initiation of an experimental rainbow trout cage farm in a small boreal lake, dramatic reductions in mysis concentrations associated with a decrease in dissolved oxygen were observed.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Significant increases in ammonium and total phosphorus, a driver for eutrophication in freshwater systems, were measured in the hypolimnion of the lake.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Annual phosphorus inputs from aquaculture waste exceeded that of natural inputs from atmospheric deposition and inflows, and phytoplankton biomass has had a fourfold annual increase following the initiation of the experimental farm.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] A type of salmon called the AquAdvantage salmon has been genetically modified for faster growth, although it has not been approved for commercial use, due to controversy.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The altered salmon incorporates a growth hormone from a Chinook salmon that allows it to reach full size in 16–28 months, instead of the normal 36 months for Atlantic salmon, and while consuming 25 percent less feed.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] A major difficulty for aquaculture is the tendency towards monoculture and the associated risk of widespread disease.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Aquaculture is also associated with environmental risks; for instance, shrimp farming has caused the destruction of important mangrove forests throughout southeast Asia.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In the 1990s, disease wiped out China's farmed Farrer's scallop and white shrimp and required their replacement by other species.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Aquaculture has an average annual growth rate of 9.2%, however, the success and continued expansion of the fish farming sector is highly dependent on the control of fish pathogens including a wide range of viruses, bacteria, fungi, and parasites.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In 2014, it was estimated that these parasites cost the global salmon farming industry up to 400 million Euros.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] This represents 6–10% of the production value of the affected countries, but it can go up to 20% (Fisheries and Oceans Canada, 2014).
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Since pathogens quickly spread within a population of cultured fish, their control is vital for the sector.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] So, this added to the efficiency of vaccines resulted in an immediate and permanent reduction in the use of antibiotics in the 90s.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In the beginning, there were fish immersion vaccines efficient against the vibriosis but proved ineffective against the furunculosis, hence the arrival of injectable vaccines: first water-based and after oil-based, much more efficient (Sommerset, 2005).
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] It is the important mortality in cages among farmed fish, the debates around DNA injection vaccines, although effective, their safety and their side effects but also societal expectations for cleaner fish and security, lead research on new vaccine vectors.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Several initiatives are financed by the European Union to develop a rapid and cost-effective approach to using bacteria in feed to make vaccines, in particular thanks to lactic bacteria whose DNA is modified (Boudinot, 2006).
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In fact, vaccinating farmed fish by injection is time-consuming and costly, so vaccines can be administered orally or by immersion by being added to feed or directly into water.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] This allows vaccinating many individuals at the same time while limiting the associated handling and stress.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Indeed, many tests are necessary because the antigens of the vaccines must be adapted to each species or not present a certain level of variability or they will not have any effect.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] There are 24 vaccines available and one for lobsters.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The first vaccine was used in the USA against enteric red mouth in 1976.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] However, there are 19 companies and some small stakeholders are producing vaccines for aquaculture nowadays.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The novel approaches are a way forward to prevent the loss of 10% of aquaculture through disease.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Genetically modified vaccines are not being used in the EU due to societal concerns and regulations.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Meanwhile, DNA vaccines are now authorised in the EU.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] There are challenges in fish vaccine development, immune response due to lack of potent adjuvants.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Scientists are considering microdose application in future.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] But there are also opportunities in aquaculture vaccinology due to the low cost of technology, regulations change and novel antigen expression and delivery systems.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In Norway subunit vaccine (VP2 peptide) against infectious pancreatic necrosis is being used.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In Canada, a licensed DNA vaccine against Infectious hematopoietic necrosis has been launched for industry use.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Fish have large mucosal surfaces, so the preferred route is immersion, intraperitoneal and oral respectively.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Nanoparticles are in progress for delivery purposes.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The common antibodies produced are IgM and IgT.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Recently these are used in cancer prevention and therapeutics.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Studies in rabies has shown that efficacy depends on dose and route of administration.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] In 2014, the aquaculture produced fish overtook wild caught fish, in supply for human food.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] This means there is a huge demand for vaccines, in prevention of diseases.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The reported annual loss fish, calculates to >10 billion USD.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] This is from approximately 10% of all fishes dying from infectious diseases.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The high annual losses increases the demand for vaccines.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Even though there are about 24 traditionally used vaccines, there is still demand for more vaccines.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The breakthrough of DNA-vaccines has sunk the cost of vaccines.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The alternative to vaccines would be antibiotics and chemotherapy, which are more expensive and with bigger drawbacks.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] DNA-vaccines have become the most cost-efficient method of preventing infectious diseases.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] This bodes well for DNA-vaccines becoming the new standard both in fish vaccines, and in general vaccines.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Sediment from abandoned aquaculture farms can remain hypersaline, acidic and eroded.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] This material can remain unusable for aquaculture purposes for long periods thereafter.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Various chemical treatments, such as adding lime, can aggravate the problem by modifying the physicochemical characteristics of the sediment.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Aquaculture produces a range of marine debris, depending on the product and location.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] The most frequently documented type of plastic is expanded polystyrene (EPS), used extensively in floats and sea cage collars (MEPC 2020).
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Other common waste items include cage nets and plastic harvest bins.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] A review of aquaculture as a source of marine litter in the North, Baltic and Mediterranean Seas identified 64 different items, 19 of which were unique to aquaculture .
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] Estimates of the amount of aquaculture waste entering the oceans vary widely, depending on the methodologies used.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p01] For example, in the European Economic Area loss estimates have varied from a low of 3,000 tonnes to 41,000 tonnes per year.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] While some forms of aquaculture can be devastating to ecosystems, such as shrimp farming in mangroves, other forms can be beneficial.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Shellfish aquaculture adds substantial filter feeding capacity to an environment which can significantly improve water quality.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] A single oyster can filter 15 gallons of water a day, removing microscopic algal cells.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] By removing these cells, shellfish are removing nitrogen and other nutrients from the system and either retaining it or releasing it as waste which sinks to the bottom.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] By harvesting these shellfish, the nitrogen they retained is completely removed from the system.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Raising and harvesting kelp and other macroalgae directly remove nutrients such as nitrogen and phosphorus.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Repackaging these nutrients can relieve eutrophic, or nutrient-rich, conditions known for their low dissolved oxygen which can decimate species diversity and abundance of marine life.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Removing algal cells from the water also increases light penetration, allowing plants such as eelgrass to reestablish themselves and further increase oxygen levels.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Aquaculture in an area can provide for crucial ecological functions for the inhabitants.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Shellfish beds or cages can provide habitat structure.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] This structure can be used as shelter by invertebrates, small fish or crustaceans to potentially increase their abundance and maintain biodiversity.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Increased shelter raises stocks of prey fish and small crustaceans by increasing recruitment opportunities in turn providing more prey for higher trophic levels.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] One study estimated that 10 square meters of oyster reef could enhance an ecosystem's biomass by 2.57 kg Herbivore shellfish will also be preyed on.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] This moves energy directly from primary producers to higher trophic levels potentially skipping out on multiple energetically costly trophic jumps which would increase biomass in the ecosystem.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Regenerative ocean farming is a polyculture farming system that grows a mix of seaweeds and shellfish while sequestering carbon, decreasing nitrogen in the water and increasing oxygen, helping to regenerate and restore local habitat like reef ecosystems.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Global wild fisheries are in decline, with valuable habitat such as estuaries in critical condition.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] The aquaculture or farming of piscivorous fish, like salmon, does not help the problem because they need to eat products from other fish, such as fish meal and fish oil.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Studies have shown that salmon farming has major negative impacts on wild salmon, as well as the forage fish that need to be caught to feed them.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Fish that are higher on the food chain are less efficient sources of food energy.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Apart from fish and shrimp, some aquaculture undertakings, such as seaweed and filter-feeding bivalve molluscs like oysters, clams, mussels and scallops, are relatively benign and even environmentally restorative.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Filter-feeders filter pollutants as well as nutrients from the water, improving water quality.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Seaweeds extract nutrients such as inorganic nitrogen and phosphorus directly from the water, and filter-feeding mollusks can extract nutrients as they feed on particulates, such as phytoplankton and detritus.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Some profitable aquaculture cooperatives promote sustainable practices.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] New methods lessen the risk of biological and chemical pollution through minimizing fish stress, fallowing netpens, and applying integrated pest management.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Vaccines are being used more and more to reduce antibiotic use for disease control.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Onshore recirculating aquaculture systems, facilities using polyculture techniques, and properly sited facilities (for example, offshore areas with strong currents) are examples of ways to manage negative environmental effects.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Recirculating aquaculture systems (RAS) recycle water by circulating it through filters to remove fish waste and food, and then recirculating it back into the tanks.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] This saves water, and the waste gathered can be used in compost or, in some cases, could even be treated and used on land.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] While RAS was developed with freshwater fish in mind, scientists associated with the Agricultural Research Service have found a way to rear saltwater fish using RAS in low-salinity waters.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Although saltwater fish are raised in offshore cages or caught with nets in water that typically has a salinity of 35 parts per thousand (ppt), scientists were able to produce healthy pompano, a saltwater fish, in tanks with a salinity of only 5 ppt.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Commercializing low-salinity RAS is predicted to have positive environmental and economic effects.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Unwanted nutrients from the fish food would not be added to the ocean, and the risk of transmitting diseases between wild and farm-raised fish would be greatly reduced.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] The price of expensive saltwater fish, such as the pompano and cobia used in the experiments, would be reduced.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Some 16 countries now use geothermal energy for aquaculture, including China, Israel, and the United States.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] In California, for example, 15 fish farms produce tilapia, bass, and catfish with warm water from underground.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] This warmer water enables fish to grow all year round and mature more quickly.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Collectively, these California farms produce 4.5 million kilograms of fish annually.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Aquaculture's contribution to GDP is not included in SDG Target 14.7, but methods for quantifying this have been explored by FAO.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Laws governing aquaculture practices vary greatly by country and are often not closely regulated or easily traceable.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] In the United States, land-based and nearshore aquaculture is regulated at the federal and state levels; no national laws govern offshore aquaculture in U.S. exclusive economic zone waters.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Facilities that produce at least 100,000 pounds (45,000 kg) of fish, molluscs or crustaceans a year are subject to specific national discharge standards.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Other permitted facilities are subject to effluent limitations that are developed on a case-by-case basis.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] The Gunditjmara, a local Aboriginal Australian people in south-western Victoria, Australia, may have raised short-finned eels as early as about 4,580 BCE.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Evidence indicates they developed about 100 km2 (39 sq mi) of volcanic floodplains in the vicinity of Lake Condah into a complex of channels and dams, and used woven traps to capture eels, and to preserve them to eat all year round.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] The local Budj Bim Cultural Landscape, a World Heritage Site, is one of the oldest known aquaculture sites in the world.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Anthropologist Peter Sutton has disputed that these eel trapping systems qualify as aquaculture as there is no evidence they involved the breeding, feeding, protecting, or rearing of eels.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Another ancient Chinese guide to aquaculture, wriiten by Yang Yu Jing around 460 BCE, shows that carp farming was becoming more sophisticated.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] The Jiahu site in China has circumstantial archeological evidence as possibly the oldest aquaculture locations, dating from 6200BCE (about 8,200 years BP), but this is speculative.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] When the waters subsided after river floods, some fish, mainly carp, were trapped in lakes.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Early aquaculturists fed their brood using nymphs and silkworm faeces, and ate them.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Ancient Egyptians might have farmed fish (especially gilt-head bream) from Lake Bardawil about 1,500 BCE (about 3,500 BP), and they traded them with Canaan.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Japanese people cultivated seaweed by providing bamboo poles and, later, nets and oyster shells to serve as anchoring-surfaces for spores.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Romans bred fish in ponds and farmed oysters in coastal lagoons before 100 CE.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] In medieval Europe, early Christian monasteries adopted Roman aquacultural practices.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Aquaculture spread because people away from coasts and big rivers were otherwise dependent on fish which required salting in order to be preserved.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Fish was an important food source in medieval Europe, when in average 150 days per year were days of fasting and abstinence, and meat was prohibited.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Improvements in transportation during the 19th century made fresh fish easily available and inexpensive, even in inland areas, rendering aquaculture less popular.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] The 15th-century fishponds of the Trebon Basin in the present-day Czech Republic are maintained as a tentative UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Samoans practised "a traditional form of giant clam ranching".
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Hawaiians constructed oceanic fish ponds.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] A remarkable example is the "Menehune" fishpond dating from at least 1,000 years ago, at Alekoko.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Legend records its construction by the mythical Menehune dwarf-people.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] In the first half of the 18th century, German Stephan Ludwig Jacobi experimented with external fertilization of brown trout and salmon.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] He wrote an article "*Von der künstlichen Erzeugung der Forellen und Lachse*" (*On the Artificial Production of Trout and Salmon*) summarizing his findings, and earning him a reputation as the founder of artificial fish-rearing.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] By the latter decades of the 18th century, oyster-farming had begun in estuaries along the Atlantic Coast of North America.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] The word "aquaculture" appeared in an 1855 newspaper article in reference to the harvesting of ice.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] It also appeared in descriptions of the terrestrial agricultural practise of sub-irrigation in the late-19th century before becoming associated primarily with the cultivation of aquatic plant- and animal-species.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] In 1859, Stephen Ainsworth of West Bloomfield, New York, began experiments with brook trout.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] By 1864, Seth Green had established a commercial fish-hatching operation at Caledonia Springs, near Rochester, New York.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Fletcher of Concord, Massachusetts, artificial fish-hatcheries operated both in both Canada and in the United States.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] When the Dildo Island fish hatchery opened in Newfoundland in 1889, it was the largest and most advanced in the world.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] The word "aquaculture" was used in descriptions of the hatcheries experiments with cod and lobster in 1890.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] By the 1920s, the American Fish Culture Company of Carolina, Rhode Island, founded in the 1870s, was one of the leading producers of trout.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] During the 1940s, they perfected the method of manipulating the day- and night-cycle of fish so that they could be artificially spawned year-round.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-p02] Californians harvested wild kelp and attempted to manage supply around 1900, later labeling it a wartime resource.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-stewardship-council] The **Aquaculture Stewardship Council** (ASC) is an independent non-profit organisation and labelling organization that establishes protocol on farmed seafood while ensuring sustainable aquaculture.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-stewardship-council] The ASC provides producers with a certification of environmental sustainability and social responsibility.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-stewardship-council] The Aquaculture Stewardship Council was founded in 2010 by the World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF) and the Dutch Sustainable Trade Initiative (IDH) to manage and implement socially responsible aquaculture.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-stewardship-council] In February 2016, Aldin Hilbrands, Meghan Jeans, Scott Nichols, and Ling Cao joined the ASC Supervisory Board.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-stewardship-council] The ASC has standards for the 12 following species: abalone, bivalves (clams, mussels, oysters and scallops), freshwater trout, pangasius, salmon, seriola and cobia, shrimp, and tilapia.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-stewardship-council] The GSI member companies (representing over 50% of the world's global farmed salmon production) have pledged to have all their salmon farms ASC-certified by 2020.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-stewardship-council] In 2010, the ASC appointed the Accreditation Services International (ASI) to accredit and oversee certifiers of aquaculture businesses.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-stewardship-council] The ASC certifies different species groups which includes Tilapia, Salmon, Pangasius, Bivalves, Cobia and Shrimp.
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-stewardship-council] In November 2017, a Seaweed Standard was also launched by the ASC together with the Marine Stewardship Council (MSC).
[src:fish-stocks/aquaculture-stewardship-council] Certified ASC products are now available around the world in Austria, Belgium, Canada, Czech Republic, Denmark, Finland, France, Germany, Italy, Hungary, Luxembourg, Netherlands, Norway, Slovenia, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland and the United Kingdom.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] An **aquatic ecosystem** is an ecosystem found in and around a body of water, in contrast to land-based terrestrial ecosystems.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Aquatic ecosystems contain communities of organisms—**aquatic life**—that are dependent on each other and on their environment.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] The two main types of aquatic ecosystems are marine ecosystems and freshwater ecosystems.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Freshwater ecosystems may be lentic (slow moving water, including pools, ponds, and lakes); lotic (faster moving water, for example streams and rivers); and wetlands (areas where the soil is saturated or inundated for at least part of the time).
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Marine ecosystems are the largest of Earth's aquatic ecosystems and exist in waters that have a high salt content.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] These systems contrast with freshwater ecosystems, which have a lower salt content.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Marine waters cover more than 70% of the surface of the Earth and account for more than 97% of Earth's water supply and 90% of habitable space on Earth.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Seawater has an average salinity of 35 parts per thousand of water.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Actual salinity varies among different marine ecosystems.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Marine ecosystems can be divided into many zones depending upon water depth and shoreline features.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] The oceanic zone is the vast open part of the ocean where animals such as whales, sharks, and tuna live.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] The benthic zone consists of substrates below water where many invertebrates live.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] The intertidal zone is the area between high and low tides.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Other near-shore (neritic) zones can include mudflats, seagrass meadows, mangroves, rocky intertidal systems, salt marshes, coral reefs, kelp forests and lagoons.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] In the deep water, hydrothermal vents may occur where chemosynthetic sulfur bacteria form the base of the food web.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] A marine coastal ecosystem is a marine ecosystem which occurs where the land meets the ocean.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Worldwide there is about 620,000 kilometres (390,000 mi) of coastline.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Coastal habitats extend to the margins of the continental shelves, occupying about 7 percent of the ocean surface area.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Marine coastal ecosystems include many very different types of marine habitats, each with their own characteristics and species composition.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] They are characterized by high levels of biodiversity and productivity.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Organisms that live freely at the ocean surface, termed neuston, include keystone organisms like the golden seaweed *Sargassum* that makes up the Sargasso Sea, floating barnacles, marine snails, nudibranchs, and cnidarians.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Many ecologically and economically important fish species live as or rely upon neuston.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Species at the surface are not distributed uniformly; the ocean's surface provides habitat for unique neustonic communities and ecoregions found at only certain latitudes and only in specific ocean basins.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] But the surface is also on the front line of climate change and pollution.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Life on the ocean's surface connects worlds.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] From shallow waters to the deep sea, the open ocean to rivers and lakes, numerous terrestrial and marine species depend on the surface ecosystem and the organisms found there.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Freshwater ecosystems are a subset of Earth's aquatic ecosystems that include the biological communities inhabiting freshwater waterbodies such as lakes, ponds, rivers, streams, springs, bogs, and wetlands.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] They can be contrasted with marine ecosystems, which have a much higher salinity.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Freshwater habitats can be classified by different factors, including temperature, light penetration, nutrients, and vegetation.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] A lake ecosystem or lacustrine ecosystem includes biotic (living) plants, animals and micro-organisms, as well as abiotic (non-living) physical and chemical interactions.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Lake ecosystems are a prime example of lentic ecosystems (*lentic* refers to stationary or relatively still freshwater, from the Latin *lentus*, which means "sluggish"), which include ponds, lakes and wetlands, and much of this article applies to lentic ecosystems in general.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Lentic ecosystems can be compared with lotic ecosystems, which involve flowing terrestrial waters such as rivers and streams.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Together, these two ecosystems are examples of freshwater ecosystems.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Lentic systems are diverse, ranging from a small, temporary rainwater pool a few inches deep to Lake Baikal, which has a maximum depth of 1642 m.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] The general distinction between pools/ponds and lakes is vague, but Brown states that ponds and pools have their entire bottom surfaces exposed to light, while lakes do not.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] In addition, some lakes become seasonally stratified.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Ponds and pools have two regions: the pelagic open water zone, and the benthic zone, which comprises the bottom and shore regions.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Since lakes have deep bottom regions not exposed to light, these systems have an additional zone, the profundal.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] These three areas can have very different abiotic conditions and, hence, host species that are specifically adapted to live there.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] River ecosystems are flowing waters that drain the landscape, and include the biotic (living) interactions amongst plants, animals and micro-organisms, as well as abiotic (nonliving) physical and chemical interactions of its many parts.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] River ecosystems are part of larger watershed networks or catchments, where smaller headwater streams drain into mid-size streams, which progressively drain into larger river networks.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] The major zones in river ecosystems are determined by the river bed's gradient or by the velocity of the current.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Faster moving turbulent water typically contains greater concentrations of dissolved oxygen, which supports greater biodiversity than the slow-moving water of pools.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] These distinctions form the basis for the division of rivers into upland and lowland rivers.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] The food base of streams within riparian forests is mostly derived from the trees, but wider streams and those that lack a canopy derive the majority of their food base from algae.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Anadromous fish are also an important source of nutrients.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Environmental threats to rivers include loss of water, dams, chemical pollution and introduced species.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] A dam produces negative effects that continue down the watershed.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] The most important negative effects are the reduction of spring flooding, which damages wetlands, and the retention of sediment, which leads to the loss of deltaic wetlands.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] A wetland is a distinct semi-aquatic ecosystem whose groundcovers are flooded or saturated in water, either permanently, for years or decades, or only seasonally.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Flooding results in oxygen-poor (anoxic) processes taking place, especially in the soils.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Wetlands form a transitional zone between waterbodies and dry lands, and are different from other terrestrial or aquatic ecosystems due to their vegetation's roots having adapted to oxygen-poor waterlogged soils.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] They are considered among the most biologically diverse of all ecosystems, serving as habitats to a wide range of aquatic and semi-aquatic plants and animals, with often improved water quality due to plant removal of excess nutrients such as nitrates and phosphorus.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Aquatic ecosystems perform many important environmental functions.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] For example, they recycle nutrients, purify water, attenuate floods, recharge ground water and provide habitats for wildlife.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] The biota of an aquatic ecosystem contribute to its self-purification, most notably microorganisms, phytoplankton, higher plants, invertebrates, fish, bacteria, protists, aquatic fungi, and more.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] These organisms are actively involved in multiple self-purification processes, including organic matter destruction and water filtration.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] It is crucial that aquatic ecosystems are reliably self-maintained, as they also provide habitats for species that reside in them.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] In addition to environmental functions, aquatic ecosystems are also used for human recreation, and are very important to the tourism industry, especially in coastal regions.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] They are also used for religious purposes, such as religious tourism to the Jordan River by Christians, and educational purposes, such as the usage of lakes for ecological study.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] The biotic characteristics are mainly determined by the organisms that occur.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] For example, wetland plants may produce dense canopies that cover large areas of sediment or snails or geese may graze the vegetation leaving large mud flats.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Aquatic environments have relatively low oxygen levels, forcing adaptation by the organisms found there.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] For example, many wetland plants must produce aerenchyma to carry oxygen to roots.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Other biotic characteristics are more subtle and difficult to measure, such as the relative importance of competition, mutualism or predation.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] There are a growing number of cases where predation by coastal herbivores including snails, geese and mammals appears to be a dominant biotic factor.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Autotrophic organisms are producers that generate organic compounds from inorganic material.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Algae use solar energy to generate biomass from carbon dioxide and are possibly the most important autotrophic organisms in aquatic environments.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] The more shallow the water, the greater the biomass contribution from rooted and floating vascular plants.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] These two sources combine to produce the extraordinary production of estuaries and wetlands, as this autotrophic biomass is converted into fish, birds, amphibians and other aquatic species.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Chemosynthetic bacteria are found in benthic marine ecosystems.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] These organisms are able to feed on hydrogen sulfide in water that comes from volcanic vents.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Great concentrations of animals that feed on these bacteria are found around volcanic vents.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] For example, there are giant tube worms (*Riftia pachyptila*) 1.5 m in length and clams (*Calyptogena magnifica*) 30 cm long.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Heterotrophic organisms consume autotrophic organisms and use the organic compounds in their bodies as energy sources and as raw materials to create their own biomass.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Euryhaline organisms are salt tolerant and can survive in marine ecosystems, while stenohaline or salt intolerant species can only live in freshwater environments.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] An ecosystem is composed of biotic communities that are structured by biological interactions and abiotic environmental factors.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Some of the important abiotic environmental factors of aquatic ecosystems include substrate type, water depth, nutrient levels, temperature, salinity, and flow.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] It is often difficult to determine the relative importance of these factors without rather large experiments.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] There may be complicated feedback loops.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] For example, sediment may determine the presence of aquatic plants, but aquatic plants may also trap sediment, and add to the sediment through peat.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] The amount of dissolved oxygen in a water body is frequently the key substance in determining the extent and kinds of organic life in the water body.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Fish need dissolved oxygen to survive, although their tolerance to low oxygen varies among species; in extreme cases of low oxygen, some fish even resort to air gulping.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Plants often have to produce aerenchyma, while the shape and size of leaves may also be altered.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Conversely, oxygen is fatal to many kinds of anaerobic bacteria.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Nutrient levels are important in controlling the abundance of many species of algae.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] The relative abundance of nitrogen and phosphorus can in effect determine which species of algae come to dominate.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Algae are a very important source of food for aquatic life, but at the same time, if they become over-abundant, they can cause declines in fish when they decay.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Similar over-abundance of algae in coastal environments such as the Gulf of Mexico produces, upon decay, a hypoxic region of water known as a dead zone.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] The salinity of the water body is also a determining factor in the kinds of species found in the water body.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Organisms in marine ecosystems tolerate salinity, while many freshwater organisms are intolerant of salt.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] The degree of salinity in an estuary or delta is an important control upon the type of wetland (fresh, intermediate, or brackish), and the associated animal species.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Dams built upstream may reduce spring flooding, and reduce sediment accretion, and may therefore lead to saltwater intrusion in coastal wetlands.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Freshwater used for irrigation purposes often absorbs levels of salt that are harmful to freshwater organisms.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] The health of an aquatic ecosystem is degraded when the ecosystem's ability to absorb a stress has been exceeded.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] A stress on an aquatic ecosystem can be a result of physical, chemical or biological alterations to the environment.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Physical alterations include changes in water temperature, water flow and light availability.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Chemical alterations include changes in the loading rates of biostimulatory nutrients, oxygen-consuming materials, and toxins.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Biological alterations include over-harvesting of commercial species and the introduction of exotic species.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Human populations can impose excessive stresses on aquatic ecosystems.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Climate change driven by anthropogenic activities can harm aquatic ecosystems by disrupting current distribution patterns of plants and animals.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] It has negatively impacted deep sea biodiversity, coastal fish diversity, crustaceans, coral reefs, and other biotic components of these ecosystems.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Human-made aquatic ecosystems, such as ditches, aquaculture ponds, and irrigation channels, may also cause harm to naturally occurring ecosystems by trading off biodiversity with their intended purposes.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] For instance, ditches are primarily used for drainage, but their presence also negatively affects biodiversity.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] There are many examples of excessive stresses with negative consequences.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] The environmental history of the Great Lakes of North America illustrates this problem, particularly how multiple stresses, such as water pollution, over-harvesting and invasive species can combine.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] The Norfolk Broadlands in England illustrate similar decline with pollution and invasive species.
[src:fish-stocks/aquatic-ecosystem] Lake Pontchartrain along the Gulf of Mexico illustrates the negative effects of different stresses including levee construction, logging of swamps, invasive species and salt water intrusion.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] All species have geographic limits to their distribution, which are determined by their tolerance to environmental conditions, and their ability to compete successfully with other species.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] In marine environments this may be less evident than on land because there are fewer topographical boundaries, however, discontinuities still exist, produced for example by mesoscale and sub-mesoscale circulations that minimize long-distance dispersal of fish larvae.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] For fish, it is rare for an individual to reproduce randomly with all other individuals of that species within its biological range.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] There is a tendency to form a structured series of discrete populations which have a degree of reproductive isolation from each other in space, in time, or in both.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] This isolation is reflected in the development between sub-populations of genetic differences, morphological variations and exposure to different chemical regimes and parasitic species.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] Sub-populations also respond to fishing in such a way that fishing on one population appears to have no effect on the population dynamics of a neighbouring population.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] The currently accepted definition of a stock in fisheries science, is that of Begg et al.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] Stock identification is a field of fisheries science which aims to identify these subpopulations, based on a number of techniques.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] This concept is applied in sustainable development goal 14 where target 14.4 is measured a fish stock sustainability indicator 14.4.1.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] The United Nations defines straddling stocks as "stocks of fish such as pollock, which migrate between, or occur in both, the economic exclusion zones (EEZ) of one or more states and the high seas".
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] Sovereign responsibility must be worked out in collaboration with neighbouring coastal states and fishing entities.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] Usually this is done through the medium of an intergovernmental regional organisation set up for the purpose of coordinating the management of that stock.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] Straddling stocks are usually pelagic, rather than demersal.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] Demersal species move less than pelagic species, since they tend to relate to bottom topography.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] Pelagic species are more mobile, their movements influenced by ocean temperatures and the availability of zooplankton as food.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] Example pelagic fish are capelin, herring, whiting, mackerel and redfish, There are, however, a few demersal species that are straddling, such as the Greenland halibut migrates in feeding/spawning migrations to Greenland in the west and to the Faeroes in the east.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] Straddling stock can be compared with transboundary stock.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] Straddling stock range both within an EEZ as well as in the high seas.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] Transboundary stock range in the EEZs of at least two countries.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] A stock can be both transboundary and straddling.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] In fisheries science and ecology, stock assessment is an important tool in fisheries management.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] In particular, to ensure continued, healthy, fish stocks, measurements of the spawning stock biomass (the stock population capable of reproducing) allows sensible conservation strategies to be developed and maintained through the application of sustainable fishing quotas.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] The UN Food and Agriculture Organization found that stocks fished within biologically sustainable levels decreased from 90% in 1974 to 62.3% in 2021.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] The stocks for individual marine species can "boom and bust" in linked and compensatory ways.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] For example, in billfish longline fisheries, the Atlantic catch of blue marlin declined in the 1960s.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] This was accompanied by an increase in sailfish catch.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] The sailfish catch then declined from the end of the 1970s to the end of the 1980s, compensated by an increase in swordfish catch.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] As a result, the overall billfish catch remained fairly stable.
[src:fish-stocks/fish-stocks] At Georges Bank, a decline in cod during the 1960s was accompanied by a rise in flatfish, and more recently, with the collapse of the predatory Atlantic cod, lobster catches in Maine have boomed.
